    <bioghist>
      <head>Biographical Note</head>
      <p>Julia Hereford (1912-1985) received her undergraduate degree from Cumberland University in 1933 and her graduate degree from Vanderbilt University&#8217;s School of Nursing in 1936. In 1938 Hereford became an instructor at the School of Nursing,
        and after completing a Master of Arts. in teaching at the Columbia University, she became an Assistant Professor in 1943. Hereford was a member of the National League of Nursing Education&#8217;s staff in 1945. In 1947 she achieved the rank of
        Associate Professor. She was finally promoted to both a full Professor and the Dean of Vanderbilt&#8217;s School of Nursing (a title she held from 1949 to 1965).</p>
      <p>From 1958 to 1959 and 1965 to 1968 Hereford took a leave of absence to finish her PhD at the University of Chicago. After completing her doctorate in 1972, Hereford became Vanderbilt&#8217;s first director of academic advising until she officially
        retired in 1977. However, she continued to participate as a Professor Emeritus until the early 1980s.</p>
      <p>Hereford passed away in 1985. The Julia Hereford Society was established to both honor her, and support the School of Nursing.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
      <p>This collection is composed of one box with thirteen folders and one book within. Researchers will find materials from Herefords&#8217; education, including her doctoral thesis, as well as materials from her tenure at Vanderbilt University.
        Furthermore, there is a large compilation of photographs of both her and her peers archived in the collection. Finally, there is correspondence to Hereford and condolences following her death.</p>
    </scopecontent>
